[src:splines-regression/b-spline] A B-spline is defined as a piecewise polynomial of order n , meaning a degree of $n-1$ .
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] It is built from sections that meet at these knots, where the continuity of the function and its derivatives depends on how often each knot repeats (its multiplicity).
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Any spline function of a specific degree can be uniquely expressed as a linear combination of B-splines of that degree over the same knots, a property that makes them versatile in mathematical modeling.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] A special subtype, cardinal B-splines, uses equidistant knots.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] The concept of B-splines traces back to the 19th century, when Nikolai Lobachevsky explored similar ideas at Kazan University in Russia, though the term "B-spline" was coined by Isaac Jacob Schoenberg in 1967, reflecting their role as basis functions.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] B-splines are widely used in fields like computer-aided design (CAD) and computer graphics, where they shape curves and surfaces through a set of control points, as well as in data analysis for tasks like curve fitting and numerical differentiation of experimental data.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] A B-spline of order $p+1$ is a collection of piecewise polynomial functions $B_{i,p}(t)$ of degree p in a variable t .
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] The values of t where the pieces of polynomial meet are known as knots, denoted $t_{0},t_{1},t_{2},\ldots ,t_{m}$ and sorted into nondecreasing order.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] for all t between the knots $t_{p}$ and $t_{m-p}$ , then the scaling factor of $B_{i,p}(t)$ becomes fixed.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] The knots in-between (and not including) $t_{p}$ and $t_{m-p}$ are called the internal knots.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] B-splines can be constructed by means of the Cox–de Boor recursion formula.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] We start with the B-splines of degree $p=0$ , i.e. piecewise constant polynomials.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] A B-spline function is a combination of flexible bands that is controlled by a number of points that are called control points, creating smooth curves.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] These functions are used to create and manage complex shapes and surfaces using a number of points.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] B-spline function and Bézier functions are applied extensively in shape optimization methods.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] A B-spline of order n is a piecewise polynomial function of degree $n-1$ in a variable x .
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] It is defined over n locations $t_{i}$ , called knots or breakpoints, which must be in non-descending order $t_{i}\leq t_{i+1}$ .
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] The B-spline contributes only in the range between the first and last of these knots and is zero elsewhere.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] If each knot is separated by the same distance h (where $h=t_{i+1}-t_{i}$ ) from its predecessor, the knot vector and the corresponding B-splines are called "uniform" (see cardinal B-spline below).
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] For each finite knot interval where it is non-zero, a B-spline is a polynomial of degree $n-1$ .
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] A B-spline is a continuous function at the knots.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] When all knots belonging to the B-spline are distinct, its derivatives are also continuous up to the derivative of degree $n-2$ .
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] If the knots are coincident at a given value of x , the continuity of derivative order is reduced by 1 for each additional coincident knot.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] B-splines may share a subset of their knots, but two B-splines defined over exactly the same knots are identical.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] In other words, a B-spline is uniquely defined by its knots.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] One distinguishes internal knots and end points.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Internal knots cover the x -domain one is interested in.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Since a single B-spline already extends over n knots, it follows that the internal knots need to be extended with $n-1$ endpoints on each side, to give full support to the first and last B-spline, which affect the internal knot intervals.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] The values of the endpoints do not matter, usually the first or last internal knot is just repeated.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] B-splines play the role of basis functions for the spline function space, hence the name.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] This property follows from the fact that all pieces have the same continuity properties, within their individual range of support, at the knots.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] That is, $B_{i,0}(x)$ is piecewise constant one or zero indicating which knot span *x* is in (zero if knot span *i* is repeated).
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] ramps from one to zero as *x* goes from $t_{i+1}$ to $t_{i+k+1}$ .
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] The corresponding *B*s are zero outside those respective ranges.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] For example, $B_{i,1}(x)$ is a triangular function that is zero below $x=t_{i}$ , ramps to one at $x=t_{i+1}$ and back to zero at and beyond $x=t_{i+2}$ .
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] However, because B-spline basis functions have local support, B-splines are typically computed by algorithms that do not need to evaluate basis functions where they are zero, such as de Boor's algorithm.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] This relation leads directly to the FORTRAN-coded algorithm BSPLV, which generates values of the B-splines of order *n* at *x*.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] The following scheme illustrates how each piece of order *n* is a linear combination of the pieces of B-splines of order *n* − 1 to its left.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Faster variants of the de Boor algorithm have been proposed, but they suffer from comparatively lower stability.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] A cardinal B-spline has a constant separation *h* between knots.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] The cardinal B-splines for a given order *n* are just shifted copies of each other.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] They can be obtained from the simpler definition.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] The "placeholder" notation is used to indicate that the *n*-th divided difference of the function $(t-x)_{+}^{n-1}$ of the two variables *t* and *x* is to be taken by fixing *x* and considering $(t-x)_{+}^{n-1}$ as a function of *t* alone.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] A cardinal B-spline has uniformly spaced knots, therefore interpolation between the knots equals convolution with a smoothing kernel.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Convolution of the signal $\mathbf {x}$ with a rectangle function $\mathbf {h} =[1/3,1/3,1/3]$ gives first order interpolated B-spline values.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Second-order B-spline interpolation is convolution with a rectangle function twice $\mathbf {y} =\mathbf {x} *\mathbf {h} *\mathbf {h}$ ; by iterative filtering with a rectangle function, higher-order interpolation is obtained.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Fast B-spline interpolation on a uniform sample domain can be done by iterative mean-filtering.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Alternatively, a rectangle function equals sinc in Fourier domain.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Therefore, cubic spline interpolation equals multiplying the signal in Fourier domain with sinc4.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] See Irwin–Hall distribution#Special cases for algebraic expressions for the cardinal B-splines of degree 1–4.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] The term P-spline stands for "penalized B-spline".
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] It refers to using the B-spline representation where the coefficients are determined partly by the data to be fitted, and partly by an additional penalty function that aims to impose smoothness to avoid overfitting.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Two- and multidimensional P-spline approximations of data can use the face-splitting product of matrices to the minimization of calculation operations.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] which shows that there is a simple relationship between the derivative of a spline function and the B-splines of degree one less.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] B-splines where the knot positions lie in a single dimension, can be used to represent 1-d probability density functions $p(x)$ .
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] and with normalization constant constraint $\sum _{i}c_{i}=1$ .
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Here, $\mathbf {t}$ represents a vector with the j knot positions and $\mathbf {m}$ a vector with the respective knot multiplicities.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] One can therefore calculate any moment of a probability density function $p(x)$ represented by a sum of B-spline basis functions exactly, without resorting to numerical techniques.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] This means that a Bézier curve of degree n given by $m\gg n$ control points consists of about $m/n$ mostly independent segments, whereas the B-spline with the same parameters smoothly transitions from subinterval to subinterval.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] To get something comparable from a Bézier curve, one would need to impose a smoothness condition on transitions between segments, resulting in some manner of Bézier spline (for which many control points would be determined by the smoothness requirement).
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] A piecewise/composite Bézier curve is a series of Bézier curves joined with at least $C^{0}$ continuity (the last point of one curve coincides with the starting point of the next curve).
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Depending on the application, additional smoothness requirements (such as $C^{1}$ or $C^{2}$ continuity) may be added. $C^{1}$ continuous curves have identical tangents at the breakpoint (where the two curves meet). $C^{2}$ continuous curves have identical curvature at the breakpoint.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Usually in curve fitting, a set of data points is fitted with a curve defined by some mathematical function.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] For example, common types of curve fitting use a polynomial or a set of exponential functions.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] When there is no theoretical basis for choosing a fitting function, the curve may be fitted with a spline function composed of a sum of B-splines, using the method of least squares.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] where *W*(*x*) is a weight, and *y*(*x*) is the datum value at *x*.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] The coefficients $\alpha _{i}$ are the parameters to be determined.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] The knot values may be fixed or treated as parameters.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] The main difficulty in applying this process is in determining the number of knots to use and where they should be placed. de Boor suggests various strategies to address this problem.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] For instance, the spacing between knots is decreased in proportion to the curvature (2nd derivative) of the data.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] For instance, the use of B-splines for fitting single Lorentzian and Gaussian curves has been investigated.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Optimal spline functions of degrees 3–7 inclusive, based on symmetric arrangements of 5, 6, and 7 knots, have been computed and the method was applied for smoothing and differentiation of spectroscopic curves.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] In a comparable study, the two-dimensional version of the Savitzky–Golay filtering and the spline method produced better results than moving average or Chebyshev filtering.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] In computer-aided design and computer graphics applications, a spline curve is sometimes represented as $C(t)$ , a parametric curve of some real parameter t .
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] In this case the curve $C(t)$ can be treated as two or three separate coordinate functions $(x(t),y(t))$ , or $(x(t),y(t),z(t))$ .
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] The coordinate functions $x(t)$ , $y(t)$ and $z(t)$ are each spline functions, with a common set of knot values $t_{1},t_{2},\ldots ,t_{n}$ .
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] These points $P_{i}$ are commonly known as control points.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Working in reverse, a sequence of control points, knot values, and order of the B-spline define a parametric curve.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Because the B-splines are non-zero for just a finite number of knot intervals, if a single control point is moved, the corresponding change to the parametric curve is just over the parameter range of a small number knot intervals.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Because $\sum _{i}B_{i,n}(x)=1$ , and at all times each $B_{i,n}(x)\geq 0$ , then the curve remains inside the bounding box of the control points.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Also, in some sense, the curve broadly follows the control points.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] A less desirable feature is that the parametric curve does not interpolate the control points.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Usually the curve does not pass through the control points.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] A cubic B-spline curve $\mathbf {C} (t)$ with a normalized parameter $t\in [0,1]$ is defined by four nodes (i.e.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] A piecewise cubic B-spline is formed by a set of nodes and each four consecutive nodes define a cubic piece of the curve with the formulation above.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] If the first and last $n+1$ knots ( n is the degree) of the knot vector have the same value, start and end points of the curve overlap the control points, resulting clamped B-splines.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] A clamped B-spline can be divided into piecewise B-spline segments with a normalized parameter $t\in [0,1]$ , defined by four control points ${\textbf {b}}_{i}$ , ${\textbf {b}}_{i+1}$ , ${\textbf {b}}_{i+2}$ , and ${\textbf {b}}_{i+3}$ .
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] where $\mathbf {R} _{i}$ is a coefficient matrix.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] In computer-aided design, computer-aided manufacturing, and computer graphics, a powerful extension of B-splines is non-uniform rational B-splines (NURBS).
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] NURBS are essentially B-splines in homogeneous coordinates.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Like B-splines, they are defined by their order, and a knot vector, and a set of control points, but unlike simple B-splines, the control points each have a weight.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] When the weight is equal to 1, a NURBS is simply a B-spline and as such NURBS generalizes both B-splines and Bézier curves and surfaces, the primary difference being the weighting of the control points which makes NURBS curves "rational".
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] By evaluating a NURBS at various values of the parameters, the curve can be traced through space; likewise, by evaluating a NURBS surface at various values of the two parameters, the surface can be represented in Cartesian space.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Like B-splines, NURBS control points determine the shape of the curve.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Each point of the curve is computed by taking a weighted sum of a number of control points.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] The weight of each point varies according to the governing parameter.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] For a curve of degree *d*, the influence of any control point is only nonzero in *d*+1 intervals (knot spans) of the parameter space.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Within those intervals, the weight changes according to a polynomial function (basis functions) of degree *d*.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] At the boundaries of the intervals, the basis functions go smoothly to zero, the smoothness being determined by the degree of the polynomial.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] The knot vector is a sequence of parameter values that determines where and how the control points affect the NURBS curve.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] The number of knots is always equal to the number of control points plus curve degree plus one.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] Each time the parameter value enters a new knot span, a new control point becomes active, while an old control point is discarded.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] *u* is the independent variable (instead of *x*), *k* is the number of control points, *N* is a B-spline (used instead of *B*), *n* is the polynomial degree, *P* is a control point and *w* is a weight.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] The denominator is a normalizing factor that evaluates to one if all weights are one.
[src:splines-regression/b-spline] are known as the rational basis functions.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] In numerical analysis, a **cubic Hermite spline** or **cubic Hermite interpolator** is a spline where each piece is a third-degree polynomial specified in Hermite form, that is, by its values and first derivatives at the end points of the corresponding domain interval.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] Cubic Hermite splines are typically used for interpolation of numeric data specified at given argument values $x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n}$ , to obtain a continuous function.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] The data should consist of the desired function value and derivative at each $x_{k}$ .
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] (If only the values are provided, the derivatives must be estimated from them.) The Hermite formula is applied to each interval $(x_{k},x_{k+1})$ separately.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] The resulting spline will be continuous and will have continuous first derivative.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] Cubic polynomial splines can be specified in other ways, the Bezier cubic being the most common.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] However, these two methods provide the same set of splines, and data can be easily converted between the Bézier and Hermite forms; so the names are often used as if they were synonymous.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] Cubic polynomial splines are extensively used in computer graphics and geometric modeling to obtain curves or motion trajectories that pass through specified points of the plane or three-dimensional space.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] In these applications, each coordinate of the plane or space is separately interpolated by a cubic spline function of a separate parameter *t*.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] Cubic polynomial splines are also used extensively in structural analysis applications, such as Euler–Bernoulli beam theory.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] Cubic polynomial splines have also been applied to mortality analysis and mortality forecasting.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] Cubic splines can be extended to functions of two or more parameters, in several ways.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] Bicubic splines (Bicubic interpolation) are often used to interpolate data on a regular rectangular grid, such as pixel values in a digital image or altitude data on a terrain.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] Bicubic surface patches, defined by three bicubic splines, are an essential tool in computer graphics.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] Cubic splines are often called **csplines**, especially in computer graphics.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] Hermite splines are named after Charles Hermite.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] Interpolating x in an arbitrary interval $(x_{k},x_{k+1})$ is done by mapping the latter to $[0,1]$ through an affine (degree-1) change of variable.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] Note that the tangent values have been scaled by $x_{k+1}-x_{k}$ compared to the equation on the unit interval.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] The formula specified above provides the unique third-degree polynomial path between the two points with the given tangents.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] Since both Q and P are third-degree polynomials, R is at most a third-degree polynomial.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] The "expanded" column shows the representation used in the definition above.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] The "factorized" column shows immediately that $h_{10}$ and $h_{11}$ are zero at the boundaries.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] You can further conclude that $h_{01}$ and $h_{11}$ have a zero of multiplicity 2 at 0, and $h_{00}$ and $h_{10}$ have such a zero at 1, thus they have slope 0 at those boundaries.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] It shows that in a cubic Bézier patch the two control points in the middle determine the tangents of the interpolation curve at the respective outer points.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] This permits efficient evaluation of the polynomial at various values of *t* since the constant coefficients can be computed once and reused.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] A data set, $(x_{k},{\boldsymbol {p}}_{k})$ for $k=1,\ldots ,n$ , can be interpolated by applying the above procedure on each interval, where the tangents are chosen in a sensible manner, meaning that the tangents for intervals sharing endpoints are equal.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] The interpolated curve then consists of piecewise cubic Hermite splines and is globally continuously differentiable in $(x_{1},x_{n})$ .
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] The choice of tangents is not unique, and there are several options available.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] for internal points $k=2,\dots ,n-1$ , and one-sided difference at the endpoints of the data set.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] The parameter c is a *tension* parameter that must be in the interval [0, 1].
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] In some sense, this can be interpreted as the "length" of the tangent.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] Choosing *c* = 1 yields all zero tangents, and choosing *c* = 0 yields a Catmull–Rom spline in the uniform parameterization case.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] a **Catmull–Rom spline** is obtained, being a special case of a cardinal spline.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] This assumes **uniform** parameter spacing.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] The curve is named after Edwin Catmull and Raphael Rom.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] The principal advantage of this technique is that the points along the original set of points also make up the control points for the spline curve.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] Two additional points are required on either end of the curve.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] The uniform Catmull–Rom implementation can produce loops and self-intersections.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] The chordal and centripetal Catmull–Rom implementations solve this problem, but use a slightly different calculation.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] In computer graphics, Catmull–Rom splines are frequently used to get smooth interpolated motion between key frames.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] For example, most camera path animations generated from discrete key-frames are handled using Catmull–Rom splines.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] They are popular mainly for being relatively easy to compute, guaranteeing that each key frame position will be hit exactly, and also guaranteeing that the tangents of the generated curve are continuous over multiple segments.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] A Kochanek–Bartels spline is a further generalization on how to choose the tangents given the data points ${\boldsymbol {p}}_{k-1}$ , ${\boldsymbol {p}}_{k}$ and ${\boldsymbol {p}}_{k+1}$ , with three parameters possible: tension, bias and a continuity parameter.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] If a cubic Hermite spline of any of the above listed types is used for interpolation of a monotonic data set, the interpolated function will not necessarily be monotonic, but monotonicity can be preserved by adjusting the tangents.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] where $\lfloor x\rfloor$ denotes the floor function, which returns the largest integer no larger than *x*.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] The bottom equality is depicting the application of Horner's method.
[src:splines-regression/cubic-hermite-spline] This writing is relevant for tricubic interpolation, where one optimization requires computing CINT*u* sixteen times with the same *u* and different *p*.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] In mathematics, a **knot** is an embedding of the circle (*S*1) into three-dimensional Euclidean space, **R**3 (also known as **E**3).
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Often two knots are considered equivalent if they are ambient isotopic, that is, if there exists a continuous deformation of **R**3 which takes one knot to the other.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] A crucial difference between the standard mathematical and conventional notions of a knot is that mathematical knots are closed — there are no ends to tie or untie on a mathematical knot.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Physical properties such as friction and thickness also do not apply, although there are mathematical definitions of a knot that take such properties into account.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] The term *knot* is also applied to embeddings of *S* *j* in *S**n*, especially in the case *j* = *n* − 2.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] The branch of mathematics that studies knots is known as knot theory and has many relations to graph theory.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] A knot is an embedding of the circle (*S*1) into three-dimensional Euclidean space (**R**3), or the 3-sphere (*S*3), since the 3-sphere is compact.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Two knots are defined to be equivalent if there is an ambient isotopy between them.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] A knot in **R**3 (or alternatively in the 3-sphere, *S*3), can be projected onto a plane **R**2 (respectively a sphere *S*2).
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] This projection is almost always **regular**, meaning that it is injective everywhere, except at a *finite number* of crossing points, which are the projections of *only two points* of the knot, and these points are not collinear.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] In this case, by choosing a projection side, one can completely encode the isotopy class of the knot by its regular projection by recording a simple over/under information at these crossings.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] In graph theory terms, a regular projection of a knot, or knot diagram is thus a quadrivalent planar graph with over/under-decorated vertices.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] The local modifications of this graph which allow to go from one diagram to any other diagram of the same knot (up to ambient isotopy of the plane) are called Reidemeister moves.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] The simplest knot, called the unknot or trivial knot, is a round circle embedded in **R**3.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] In the ordinary sense of the word, the unknot is not "knotted" at all.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] The simplest nontrivial knots are the trefoil knot (31 in the table), the figure-eight knot (41) and the cinquefoil knot (51).
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Several knots, linked or tangled together, are called links.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Knots are links with a single component.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] A *polygonal* knot is a knot whose image in **R**3 is the union of a finite set of line segments.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] A *tame* knot is any knot equivalent to a polygonal knot.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Knots which are not tame are called *wild*, and can have pathological behavior.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] In knot theory and 3-manifold theory, often the adjective "tame" is omitted.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Smooth knots, for example, are always tame.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] A *framed knot* is the extension of a tame knot to an embedding of the solid torus *D*2 × *S*1 in *S*3.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] The *framing* of the knot is the linking number of the image of the ribbon *I* × *S*1 with the knot.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] A framed knot can be seen as the embedded ribbon and the framing is the (signed) number of twists.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] This definition generalizes to an analogous one for *framed links*.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Framed links are said to be *equivalent* if their extensions to solid tori are ambient isotopic.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Framed link *diagrams* are link diagrams with each component marked, to indicate framing, by an integer representing a slope with respect to the meridian and preferred longitude.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] A standard way to view a link diagram without markings as representing a framed link is to use the *blackboard framing*.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] This framing is obtained by converting each component to a ribbon lying flat on the plane.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] A type I Reidemeister move clearly changes the blackboard framing (it changes the number of twists in a ribbon), but the other two moves do not.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Given a knot, one can define infinitely many framings on it.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Suppose that we are given a knot with a fixed framing.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] One may obtain a new framing from the existing one by cutting a ribbon and twisting it an integer multiple of 2π around the knot and then glue back again in the place we did the cut.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] In this way one obtains a new framing from an old one, up to the equivalence relation for framed knots, leaving the knot fixed.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] The framing in this sense is associated to the number of twists the vector field performs around the knot.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Knowing how many times the vector field is twisted around the knot allows one to determine the vector field up to diffeomorphism, and the equivalence class of the framing is determined completely by this integer called the framing integer.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Given a knot in the 3-sphere, the knot complement is all the points of the 3-sphere not contained in the knot.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] A major theorem of Gordon and Luecke states that at most two knots have homeomorphic complements (the original knot and its mirror reflection).
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] This in effect turns the study of knots into the study of their complements, and in turn into 3-manifold theory.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] The JSJ decomposition and Thurston's hyperbolization theorem reduces the study of knots in the 3-sphere to the study of various geometric manifolds via *splicing* or *satellite operations*.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] In the pictured knot, the JSJ-decomposition splits the complement into the union of three manifolds: two trefoil complements and the complement of the Borromean rings.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] The trefoil complement has the geometry of **H**2 × **R**, while the Borromean rings complement has the geometry of **H**3.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Parametric representations of knots are called harmonic knots.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Aaron Trautwein compiled parametric representations for all knots up to and including those with a crossing number of 8 in his PhD thesis.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] In knot theory, the **connected sum** (or **knot sum**) $K_{1}\#K_{2}$ of two oriented knots is the natural way to combine them.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] It makes the set of oriented knot types into a commutative monoid with the unknot as identity, and the operation is central to the decomposition of knots into prime pieces.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Choose a 3‑ball $B_{i}$ that meets $K_{i}$ in a single unknotted arc.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Remove the interior of a smaller arc‑neighbourhood from each ball, obtaining a pair $(B_{i},K_{i}\cap B_{i})$ whose boundary sphere intersects the knot in two points.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] The **connected sum** is formed by gluing the exteriors $S^{3}\setminus \operatorname {int} (B_{1})$ and $S^{3}\setminus \operatorname {int} (B_{2})$ along their boundary spheres via an orientation‑reversing homeomorphism that matches the endpoints of the arcs and preserves the given orientations.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] The result is again $S^{3}$ , and the image of the two arcs is a new oriented knot.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] The construction does not depend on the choices of balls, arcs, or gluing map; any two connected sums of the same oriented knots are isotopic.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] In practice one often draws the connected sum by taking knot diagrams of the two knots, cutting a small arc from each diagram and joining the loose ends without introducing new crossings, respecting orientations.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] If the knots are not oriented, the result may depend on the relative orientation, because some knots are non‑invertible.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Standard practice is to work with oriented knots.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] A knot is **prime** if it is non‑trivial and not a connected sum of two non‑trivial knots.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Every non‑trivial oriented knot decomposes as a connected sum of prime knots.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] The decomposition is unique up to the order of the factors.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Thus the monoid of oriented knot types is a free commutative monoid on the set of prime knots.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] The unknot plays the role of the unit, analogous to the number 1.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] For links of more than one component, unique decomposition fails.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] The multiplicativity of the Alexander, Jones, and HOMFLY polynomials follows immediately from the skein relations.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] For ordered links, the connected sum can be performed on chosen components, but the result depends on the choice of components and the ordering.
[src:splines-regression/knot-mathematics] Unlike for knots, the monoid of links is not free and factorisation into prime links is not unique.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] Let $\{x_{i},Y_{i}:i=1,\dots ,n\}$ be a set of observations, modeled by the relation $Y_{i}=f(x_{i})+\epsilon _{i}$ where the $\epsilon _{i}$ are independent, zero mean random variables.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] From these values, derive ${\hat {f}}(x)$ for all *x*.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] Given the vector ${\hat {m}}=({\hat {f}}(x_{1}),\ldots ,{\hat {f}}(x_{n}))^{T}$ of fitted values, the sum-of-squares part of the spline criterion is fixed.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] It remains only to minimize $\int {\hat {f}}''(x)^{2}\,dx$ , and the minimizer is a natural cubic spline that interpolates the points $(x_{i},{\hat {f}}(x_{i}))$ .
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] where $f_{i}(x)$ are a set of spline basis functions.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] The basis functions, and hence the matrix A , depend on the configuration of the predictor variables $x_{i}$ , but not on the responses $Y_{i}$ or ${\hat {m}}$ .
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] A is an $n\times n$ matrix given by $A=\Delta ^{T}W^{-1}\Delta$ .
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] Minimizing over ${\hat {m}}$ by differentiating against ${\hat {m}}$ .
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] De Boor's approach exploits the same idea, of finding a balance between having a smooth curve and being close to the given data.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] where p is a parameter called smooth factor and belongs to the interval $[0,1]$ , and $\delta _{i};i=1,\dots ,n$ are the quantities controlling the extent of smoothing (they represent the weight $\delta _{i}^{-2}$ of each point $Y_{i}$ ).
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] In practice, since cubic splines are mostly used, m is usually 2 .
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] The solution for $m=2$ was proposed by Christian Reinsch in 1967.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] For $m=2$ , when p approaches 1 , ${\hat {f}}$ converges to the "natural" spline interpolant to the given data.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] As p approaches 0 , ${\hat {f}}$ converges to a straight line (the smoothest curve).
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] Since finding a suitable value of p is a task of trial and error, a redundant constant S was introduced for convenience.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] The algorithm described by de Boor starts with $p=0$ and increases p until the condition is met.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] If $\delta _{i}$ is an estimation of the standard deviation for $Y_{i}$ , the constant S is recommended to be chosen in the interval $\left[n-{\sqrt {2n}},n+{\sqrt {2n}}\right]$ .
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] Having $S=0$ means the solution is the "natural" spline interpolant.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] Increasing S means we obtain a smoother curve by getting farther from the given data.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] There are two main classes of method for generalizing from smoothing with respect to a scalar x to smoothing with respect to a vector x .
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] The first approach simply generalizes the spline smoothing penalty to the multidimensional setting.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] The thin plate spline approach can be generalized to smoothing with respect to more than two dimensions and to other orders of differentiation in the penalty.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] As the dimension increases there are some restrictions on the smallest order of differential that can be used, but actually Duchon's original paper, gives slightly more complicated penalties that can avoid this restriction.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] The thin plate splines are isotropic, meaning that if we rotate the $x,z$ co-ordinate system the estimate will not change, but also that we are assuming that the same level of smoothing is appropriate in all directions.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] This is often considered reasonable when smoothing with respect to spatial location, but in many other cases isotropy is not an appropriate assumption and can lead to sensitivity to apparently arbitrary choices of measurement units.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] For example, if smoothing with respect to distance and time an isotropic smoother will give different results if distance is measure in metres and time in seconds, to what will occur if we change the units to centimetres and hours.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] The second class of generalizations to multi-dimensional smoothing deals directly with this scale invariance issue using tensor product spline constructions.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] Such splines have smoothing penalties with multiple smoothing parameters, which is the price that must be paid for not assuming that the same degree of smoothness is appropriate in all directions.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] Source code for spline smoothing can be found in the examples from Carl de Boor's book *A Practical Guide to Splines*.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] The examples are in the Fortran programming language.
[src:splines-regression/regression-spline] The updated sources are available also on Carl de Boor's official site .
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] In mathematics, a **spline** is a function defined piecewise by polynomials.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] In interpolating problems, spline interpolation is often preferred to polynomial interpolation because it yields similar results, even when using low degree polynomials, while avoiding Runge's phenomenon for higher degrees.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] In the computer science subfields of computer-aided design and computer graphics, the term *spline* more frequently refers to a piecewise polynomial (parametric) curve.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] Splines are popular curves in these subfields because of the simplicity of their construction, their ease and accuracy of evaluation, and their capacity to approximate complex shapes through curve fitting and interactive curve design.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] The term spline comes from the flexible spline devices used by shipbuilders and draftsmen to draw smooth shapes.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] The term "spline" is used to refer to a wide class of functions that are used in applications requiring data interpolation and/or smoothing.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] The data may be either one-dimensional or multi-dimensional.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] Spline functions for interpolation are normally determined as the minimizers of suitable measures of roughness (for example integral squared curvature) subject to the interpolation constraints.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] Smoothing splines may be viewed as generalizations of interpolation splines where the functions are determined to minimize a weighted combination of the average squared approximation error over observed data and the roughness measure.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] For a number of meaningful definitions of the roughness measure, the spline functions are found to be finite dimensional in nature, which is the primary reason for their utility in computations and representation.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] For the rest of this section, we focus entirely on one-dimensional, polynomial splines and use the term "spline" in this restricted sense.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] According to Gerald Farin, B-splines were explored as early as the nineteenth century by Nikolai Lobachevsky at Kazan University in Russia.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] Before computers were used, numerical calculations were done by hand.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] Although piecewise-defined functions like the sign function or step function were used, polynomials were generally preferred because they were easier to work with.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] Through the advent of computers, splines have gained importance.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] They were first used as a replacement for polynomials in interpolation, then as a tool to construct smooth and flexible shapes in computer graphics.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] It is commonly accepted that the first mathematical reference to splines is the 1946 paper by Schoenberg, which is probably the first place that the word "spline" is used in connection with smooth, piecewise polynomial approximation.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] However, the ideas have their roots in the aircraft and shipbuilding industries.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] For years the practice of ship design had employed models to design in the small.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] The successful design was then plotted on graph paper and the key points of the plot were re-plotted on larger graph paper to full size.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] The thin wooden strips provided an interpolation of the key points into smooth curves.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] The strips would be held in place at discrete points (called "ducks" by Forrest; Schoenberg used "dogs" or "rats") and between these points would assume shapes of minimum strain energy.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] According to Forrest, one possible impetus for a mathematical model for this process was the potential loss of the critical design components for an entire aircraft should the loft be hit by an enemy bomb.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] This gave rise to "conic lofting", which used conic sections to model the position of the curve between the ducks.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] Conic lofting was replaced by what we would call splines in the early 1960s based on work by J.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] Ferguson at Boeing and (somewhat later) by Malcolm A.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] The word "spline" was originally an East Anglian dialect word.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] The use of splines for modeling automobile bodies seems to have several independent beginnings.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] Credit is claimed on behalf of de Casteljau at Citroën, Pierre Bézier at Renault, and Birkhoff, Garabedian, and de Boor at General Motors (see Birkhoff and de Boor, 1965), all for work occurring in the very early 1960s or late 1950s.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] At least one of de Casteljau's papers was published, but not widely, in 1959.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] De Boor's work at General Motors resulted in a number of papers being published in the early 1960s, including some of the fundamental work on B-splines.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] Work was also being done at Pratt & Whitney Aircraft, where two of the authors of (Ahlberg et al., 1967) — the first book-length treatment of splines — were employed, and the David Taylor Model Basin, by Feodor Theilheimer.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] The work at General Motors is detailed nicely in (Birkhoff, 1990) and (Young, 1997).
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] Davis (1997) summarizes some of this material.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] We begin by limiting our discussion to polynomials in one variable.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] In this case, a spline is a piecewise polynomial function.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] This function, call it S, takes values from an interval [*a*,*b*] and maps them to $\mathbb {R} ,$ the set of real numbers, $S:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R} .$ We want S to be piecewise defined.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] The given *k* + 1 points ti are called **knots**.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] The vector **t** = (*t*0, …, *tk*) is called a **knot vector** for the spline.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] If the knots are equidistantly distributed in the interval [*a*,*b*] we say the spline is **uniform**, otherwise we say it is **non-uniform**.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] If the polynomial pieces Pi each have degree at most n, then the spline is said to be of **degree** ≤ *n* (or of **order** *n* + 1).
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] If $S\in C^{r_{i}}$ in a neighborhood of ti, then the spline is said to be of smoothness (at least) $C^{r_{i}}$ at ti.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] A vector **r** = (*r*1, …, *r**k*–1) such that the spline has smoothness $C^{r_{i}}$ at ti for *i* = 1, …, *k* – 1 is called a **smoothness vector** for the spline.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] Given a knot vector **t**, a degree n, and a smoothness vector **r** for **t**, one can consider the set of all splines of degree ≤ *n* having knot vector **t** and smoothness vector **r**.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] Equipped with the operation of adding two functions (pointwise addition) and taking real multiples of functions, this set becomes a real vector space.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] In the mathematical study of polynomial splines the question of what happens when two knots, say ti and *t**i*+1, are taken to approach one another and become coincident has an easy answer.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] The polynomial piece *Pi*(*t*) disappears, and the pieces *P**i*−1(*t*) and *P**i*+1(*t*) join with the sum of the smoothness losses for ti and *t**i*+1.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] This leads to a more general understanding of a knot vector.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] where ti is repeated ji times for *i* = 1, …, *k* – 1.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] A parametric curve on the interval [*a*,*b*] $G(t)={\bigl (}X(t),Y(t){\bigr )},\quad t\in [a,b]$ is a **spline curve** if both X and Y are spline functions of the same degree with the same extended knot vectors on that interval.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] Suppose the polynomial pieces are to be of degree 2, and the pieces on [0, 1] and [1, 2] must join in value and first derivative (at *t* = 1) while the pieces on [1, 2] and [2, 3] join simply in value (at *t* = 2).
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] (Note: while the polynomial piece 2*t* is not quadratic, the result is still called a quadratic spline.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] This demonstrates that the degree of a spline is the maximum degree of its polynomial parts.) The extended knot vector for this type of spline would be (0, 1, 2, 2, 3).
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] The next most simple spline has degree 1.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] A closed linear spline (i.e, the first knot and the last are the same) in the plane is just a polygon.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] A common spline is the **natural cubic spline**.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] A cubic spline has degree 3 with continuity *C*2, i.e. the values and first and second derivatives are continuous.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] Natural means that the second derivatives of the spline polynomials are zero at the endpoints of the interval of interpolation.
[src:splines-regression/spline-mathematics] Thus, the graph of the spline is a straight line outside of the interval, but still smooth.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] The name *thin plate spline* refers to a physical analogy involving the bending of a plate or thin sheet of metal.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] Just as the metal has rigidity, the TPS fit resists bending also, implying a penalty involving the smoothness of the fitted surface.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] In the physical setting, the deflection is in the z direction, orthogonal to the plane.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] In order to apply this idea to the problem of coordinate transformation, one interprets the lifting of the plate as a displacement of the x or y coordinates within the plane.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] In 2D cases, given a set of K corresponding control points (knots), the TPS warp is described by $2(K+3)$ parameters which include 6 global affine motion parameters and $2K$ coefficients for correspondences of the control points.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] These parameters are computed by solving a linear system, in other words, TPS has a closed-form solution.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] The TPS arises from consideration of the integral of the square of the second derivative—this forms its smoothness measure.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] For this variational problem, it can be shown that there exists a unique minimizer f .
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] The finite element discretization of this variational problem, the method of elastic maps, is used for data mining and nonlinear dimensionality reduction.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] In simple words, "the first term is defined as the error measurement term and the second regularisation term is a penalty on the smoothness of f ." It is in a general case needed to make the mapping unique.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] The thin plate spline has a natural representation in terms of radial basis functions.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] where $\left\|\cdot \right\|$ denotes the usual Euclidean norm and $\{w_{i}\}$ is a set of mapping coefficients.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] The TPS corresponds to the radial basis kernel $\varphi (r)=r^{2}\log r$ .
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] Suppose the points are in 2 dimensions ( $D=2$ ).
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] One can use *homogeneous coordinates* for the point-set where a point $y_{i}$ is represented as a vector $(1,y_{ix},y_{iy})$ .
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] The unique minimizer f is parameterized by $\alpha$ which consists of two matrices d and c ( $\alpha =\{d,c\}$ ).
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] where d is a $(D+1)\times (D+1)$ matrix representing the affine transformation (hence z is a $1\times (D+1)$ vector) and c is a $K\times (D+1)$ warping coefficient matrix representing the non-affine deformation.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] Note that for TPS, the control points $\{c_{i}\}$ are chosen to be the same as the set of points to be warped $\{x_{i}\}$ , so we already use $\{x_{i}\}$ in the place of the control points.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] where Y and X are just concatenated versions of the point coordinates $y_{i}$ and $x_{i}$ , and $\Phi$ is a $(K\times K)$ matrix formed from the $\phi (\|x_{i}-x_{j}\|)$ .
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] Each row of each newly formed matrix comes from one of the original vectors.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] The matrix $\Phi$ represents the TPS kernel.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] Loosely speaking, the TPS kernel contains the information about the point-set's internal structural relationships.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] When it is combined with the warping coefficients c , a non-rigid warping is generated.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] A nice property of the TPS is that it can always be decomposed into a global affine and a local non-affine component.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] Consequently, the TPS smoothness term is solely dependent on the non-affine components.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] This is a desirable property, especially when compared to other splines, since the global pose parameters included in the affine transformation are not penalized.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] TPS has been widely used as the non-rigid transformation model in image alignment and shape matching.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] An additional application is the analysis and comparisons of archaeological findings in 3D and was implemented for triangular meshes in the GigaMesh Software Framework.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] There are no free parameters that need manual tuning.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] It has closed-form solutions for both warping and parameter estimation.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] There is a physical explanation for its energy function.
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] However, note that splines already in one dimension can cause severe "overshoots".
[src:splines-regression/thin-plate-spline] In 2D such effects can be much more critical, because TPS are not objective.
